### Description

When using a spy (with `spyOn()`), the spied-on function prevents its code from being run. So

```ts
// mycomponent.spec.ts
const fixture = TestBed.createComponent(MyComponent);
const component = fixture.componentInstance;
const myspy = spyOn(component, 'someFunc');

// when
doSomething();

// then 
expect(myspy).toHaveBeenCalled(); // Success
expect(component.someValue).toBe(true); // Fail
```
```ts
// mycomponent.ts
someFunc = () => {
  console.log('hello?');
  this.someValue = true;
}
```

When spying on `someFunc`, the spy works for its intended purpose (seeing whether it's been called), but then immediately quits before running the code within. So any other checks, such as the second `expect` in this example, fail. Removing the spy makes the code run as expected.
The same goes for e.g. a console.log I put at the top of that function, so it's not just the actual check that somehow fails.

